7:
The elder passed away a month
ago—in her sleep. She didn't suffer.
11:
S-seriously?! I thought she was
gonna live forever... I can't believe it!
14:
We sent word to Palpebra to inform
you, but you were nowhere to be
found. One wonders what you were
doing...
17:
I was in a different wor—I mean, I
was away on a business trip. Yes,
that's right.
20:
A-anyway! Did the elder leave
behind anything for me? Any last
words?
23:
Yes, in fact. However, all that she
had to say was entrusted to Dul
Kugala...
27:
R-really? You mean to say she's the
new elder?!
29:
Quite a commotion stirring up here, I
see.
32:
Even from inside my tent, I could
hear every single word out of your
mouth, Mal Lelucia.
36: Dul Kugala... Long time no see.
45:
You know what, Stella? Let's just get
out of here—we can go look for
clues on another world instead!
49:
Mal Lelucia. Do you really intend on
disappearing without offering even
a single prayer in the name of our
deceased elder?
52:
Don't worry, I'll refrain from asking
any prying questions about your
business enterprises—this time, at
least.
55:
Plus, I have a favor to ask of these
two you've brought. If they're willing
to hear me out, I'll gladly disclose
some of our people's deeply held
secrets.
63:
You're Alk and Stella, are you not?
You two have been a great help to
Pur Lilie.
67:
Allow me to introduce myself. My
name is Dul Kugala. I am an
executive on the Guild High
Council—and, as of recently, the
Elder of my people.
69:
I am pleased to finally make your
acquaintance.
If you would follow me inside.
73:
Don't worry, I'm sure Lilie would
never have used your real names.
Dul Kugala probably had you
specifically vetted...
76:
An executive from the Guild... Surely
we're on the same side here. I doubt
she will be hostile to us.
80:
You're right, but don't underestimate
her. She comes from a family that's
known for being... quite driven. She's
a shrewd one.
84:
Not exactly the type of person I get
along with best, if you catch my drift.
93:
Yes, of a small settlement just on the
outskirts. Fortunately no blood has
been spilled yet, but all of the
residents were driven out forcefully.
96:
That brings me to my request: I
would like you to undertake an
investigation to uncover the truth
about these invaders—as well as the
scale of their operation.
101:
But... this isn't exactly an odd case,
right? Things like this happen from
time to time, don't they?
105:
Indeed, adventurers who have fallen
on hard times often resort to
brigandry and commit similar acts.
108:
But, as you've likely already
surmised, we wouldn't be asking for
your aid if this were a normal
incident.
110:
One key factor is different this time:
the location. Have you ever heard of
the branches of the Kaleidoscope?
115: Oh boy, I don't like the sound of that...
118:
Those are exactly what they sound
like—paths that split off from the
Kaleidoscope and lead up to the
surface. They're usually extremely
narrow...
122:
But they are nonetheless entry
points into the Kaleidoscope proper.
Left unattended, they become a
hotbed for illicit smuggling.
124:
For that reason, we post tight
security on all exits, and keep their
whereabouts strictly confidential.
128:
So this "settlement" was actually just
there to watch the branch
entrance? Figures.
132:
One final question remains,
however:
Where did these people come from?
135:
A group of their scale—about a few
dozen or so—is certain to leave
some sort of traces of migration.
And yet, surveys of nearby areas
have yielded nothing.
139:
Meaning they could have come
from within the Kaleidoscope and
passed through a branch.
142:
I think it's reasonable to assume
that. The problem, however, is the
scale of their group. It's simply
unprecedented.
144:
We felt you were the most suited for
this job, given that it involves
travelers from another world
appearing in a secret location.
148:
To be clear... This is just a survey
mission—you're not asking us to
fight them, right?
151:
That is correct. At this stage, our
goal is to assess the situation. We
will, of course, be offering you some
support.
153: I trust we can count on you, Zekhel?
157:
Bah. And here I was thinking I'd get
away with not having to do any
work. Bummer.
166:
My name's Zekhel. As you can
probably tell, I'm a member of the
Guild Knights. These days I mostly
go around doing Kugala's bidding.
168:
So, you heard the scoop. Are you in,
or are you out? If you're in, we're
leaving lickity split.
172: What if we were to refuse?
176:
Nothing will come of it. You have my
word that you will not be negatively
affected.
180:
Well. Iunno about "nothing." It'll
mean I have way more work to do.
185:
I see no issues with accepting this
request, but I will respect whatever
decision you two make. What do
you think?
193:
Let's do it. I think it's worth getting to
the bottom of this!
198:
Alrighty then. How's about we get
going on our merry little way? Here's
to hoping you folks are good travel
partners.
212:
Thank you for your help everyone. I
look forward to hearing good news.
